./.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/002-resource-map-deep-loop-fix/003-resource-map-deep-loop-integration/research/iterations/iteration-003.md:9:3. Child-phase safety depends on never re-running `resolveArtifactRoot()` inside the convergence emitter. The shared helper allocates the next `{phaseSlug}-pt-{NN}` subfolder by counting existing packet directories each time it resolves a child phase, and both reducers currently call that helper internally. A convergence-time emitter that resolves again could therefore drift into a sibling packet on repeat runs. The safe contract is: resolve `{artifact_dir}` once in YAML init, carry that resolved path through `state_paths`, and have the emitter and extractor consume the fixed path directly. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs:18] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs:41] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs:77] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs:117] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/spec_kit/assets/spec_kit_deep-research_auto.yaml:98] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/spec_kit/assets/spec_kit_deep-review_auto.yaml:89] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/scripts/reduce-state.cjs:823] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-review/scripts/reduce-state.cjs:1141]
./.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/002-resource-map-deep-loop-fix/003-resource-map-deep-loop-integration/research/iterations/iteration-003.md:10:4. The packet's opt-out/config wording needs revision to match the live config style and workflow ownership split. The live deep-research config schema is camelCase and treats `{artifact_dir}` packet files as workflow-owned outputs, while the phase-013 packet currently specifies reducer-local emission plus a snake_case `config.resource_map.emit` field. The implementation contract should instead add a workflow-owned config field consistent with the existing JSON schema naming, then document the CLI flag and synthesis-step skip behavior across command + skill surfaces. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/references/state_format.md:17] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/references/state_format.md:25] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/references/state_format.md:45] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/011-resource-map-template/003-resource-map-deep-loop-integration/spec.md:81] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/011-resource-map-template/003-resource-map-deep-loop-integration/spec.md:83] [INFERENCE: the production config field should follow the existing camelCase config schema rather than introduce a one-off snake_case branch.]
./.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/002-resource-map-deep-loop-fix/003-resource-map-deep-loop-integration/research/iterations/iteration-003.md:11:5. The lowest-coupling doc/test updates are anchored to existing synthesis surfaces, and the packet's wildcard "create a new resource-map-emission file everywhere" list is too coarse. Both command entrypoints, both SKILL.md files, both existing synthesis feature-catalog files, and the final-synthesis manual playbooks currently describe only `research.md` or `review-report.md` as terminal artifacts. Those existing files are the authoritative places to extend the synthesis contract. In addition, both playbook suites still contain stale notes claiming no dedicated feature catalog exists even though `feature_catalog/` is present for both skills, so the doc update set needs to fix that drift as part of phase 013. [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/spec_kit/deep-research.md:183] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/spec_kit/deep-review.md:194] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/SKILL.md:287] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-review/SKILL.md:295] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/feature_catalog/01--loop-lifecycle/04-synthesis.md:18] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-review/feature_catalog/01--loop-lifecycle/04-synthesis.md:25] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/manual_testing_playbook/06--synthesis-save-and-guardrails/019-final-synthesis-memory-save-and-guardrail-behavior.md:67] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-review/manual_testing_playbook/06--synthesis-save-and-guardrails/027-final-synthesis-memory-save-and-guardrail-behavior.md:67] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:593]
./.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/002-resource-map-deep-loop-fix/003-resource-map-deep-loop-integration/research/iterations/iteration-003.md:15:- Re-resolving artifact roots inside the emitter or extractor. Child-phase packet allocation is not stable across repeated fresh resolves, so the emitter must inherit the already-resolved `{artifact_dir}` from workflow state instead. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs:31] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/shared/review-research-paths.cjs:117] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/scripts/reduce-state.cjs:823]
./.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/002-resource-map-deep-loop-fix/003-resource-map-deep-loop-integration/research/iterations/iteration-003.md:18:- Treating the packet's current file list as "new standalone feature/playbook docs everywhere" without first updating the existing synthesis docs. The shipped synthesis feature files and finalization playbooks are already the authoritative contract surface, so ignoring them would leave the main operator-facing sources stale even if new helper docs were added. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/feature_catalog/01--loop-lifecycle/04-synthesis.md:24] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-review/feature_catalog/01--loop-lifecycle/04-synthesis.md:31] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/manual_testing_playbook/06--synthesis-save-and-guardrails/019-final-synthesis-memory-save-and-guardrail-behavior.md:60] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-review/manual_testing_playbook/06--synthesis-save-and-guardrails/027-final-synthesis-memory-save-and-guardrail-behavior.md:60]
