./.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/002-resource-map-deep-loop-fix/003-resource-map-deep-loop-integration/research/findings-registry.json:414:        "`.opencode/skills/sk-deep-review/manual_testing_playbook/06--synthesis-save-and-guardrails/027-final-synthesis-memory-save-and-guardrail-behavior.md:24`"
./.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/002-resource-map-deep-loop-fix/003-resource-map-deep-loop-integration/research/findings-registry.json:419:      "text": "The shared extractor API should be shaped around per-iteration delta files, not the packet's imagined nested `findings[]` payloads. The live contract is one JSONL file per iteration containing one canonical `{\"type\":\"iteration\",...}` row plus event rows, and the phase-012 template only exposes `Path | Action | Status | Note` plus summary counts. That means the stable boundary is a two-stage API such as `collectResourceMapEvidence({ mode, deltaFiles, repoRoot }) -> { rows, summary, degraded }` followed by `renderResourceMap({ rows, summary, scope, generatedAt }) -> markdown`, where review counts and research citation totals are encoded in `Note` text and summary totals instead of custom columns. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/assets/prompt_pack_iteration.md.tmpl:40] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/spec_kit/assets/spec_kit_deep-research_auto.yaml:108] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-deep-review/assets/review_mode_contract.yaml:307] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/templates/resource-map.md:39] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/templates/resource-map.md:67] [INFERENCE: keeping extraction and rendering separate matches the live JSONL event stream while preserving the locked template's single `Note` escape hatch for counts.]",
./.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/002-resource-map-deep-loop-fix/003-resource-map-deep-loop-integration/research/findings-registry.json:427:        "`.opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/assets/deep_research_config.json:1`",
